* This course will open every 2 years.
※Graduation requirement:
Required courses: 21 credits
Elective courses: 9 credits
Thesis: 6 credits
 
● Required  courses
Nursing Research   3 credits
This course provides an introduction to the theories and methods applied in nursing research. Students develop ability to critique literature, analyze and integrate research findings in means to formulate and propose a feasible research proposal. Research design, measurement and statistical analysis will also be introduced throughout the course. 
 
Advanced Nursing Practicum (I)  3 credits
The first part of the two-level course aims to advance students’ clinical professional competence based on individual professional background and future career planning. Students will participate in a variety of health assessment and activities at clinical or community settings, such as clinical skills center, NCKU hospital, community or long-term care facilities. Students will learn to assess clients’ health care problems or needs and provide appropriate care through nursing process by integrating various medical knowledge, including clinical diagnosis, pharmacology, nutrition, and physical examination skills. Students will apply evidence-based concept on implementing an effective and proficient nursing care to solve the problem. For community nursing, students will design an effective health care plan through conducting community assessment, community diagnosis, health care planning, implementation and outcome evaluation.
 
 Advanced Nursing Practicum (II)  3 credits
The second part of this two-level course continues to fulfill the purpose of advancing students’ clinical professional competence. Students will be arranged to practice in either NCKU hospital, local community or long-term care facilities according to individual professional back ground and learning objectives. Students will integrate and synthesize knowledge with skills from all foundation, core and specialty courses, develop competency in assessing and diagnosing clients’ health care problems. Evidence-based practices will be used to identify effective strategies and practice to resolve the clients’ problems. For community nursing specialty, special emphasis is placed on developing competencies in the area of community assessment, community diagnosis, health care planning, implementation and outcome evaluation.
 
Data Analysis and Management in Health Care   3 credits
This course provides basic introduction of biometrics and techniques used in statistical analysis. With the use of statistical software and program, students will develop the ability to manage, analyze and interpret health related data and information retrieving from the internet. Specific topics include basic biometrics, applications related to nursing research, such as uses of EXCEL & SPSS, generation of statistical figures and tables, and information search for health care issues will be covered in this course.
 
Health and Physical Assessment and Examination   3credits
This course is aimed to advance students’ skills in interviewing patients, health history taking, and head to toes physical examination. Students will be guided to integrate background knowledge and apply physical examination techniques to discriminate and analyze abnormal physical conditions in order to make clinical decision.
 
Bio- and Medical Ethics  2credits
This course is designed to assist students to understand the major bioethical principles（autonomy, beneficence, nonmaleficence, justice）and explore the effects of ethical training on clinical judgments. Ethical decision-making models are introduced to analyze dilemmas arose in clinical practices. Students are expected to develop motivation and capability to recognize and analyze ethical issues, and to determine appropriate actions for ethical dilemmas.
 
Seminar In Nursing Education  2 credits
The purpose of this course is to develop students’ professional as a role of educator in nursing. Specific topics including the SWOT analysis, current trends in nursing education, curriculum design with evaluation in medical education, adult learning in nursing and innovative teaching strategies will be covered in this course. Students will have the opportunity to practice effective teaching strategies such as innovative didactic teaching, creative strategies in simulations and technology-assisted strategies in class. Students are expected to be able to design and re-modify course syllabus and instructional methods for a nursing education program.
 
Evidence-based Health Care   2 credits
The purpose of this course is to introduce the conscientious use of the most prominent and up-to-date evidence in making decisions to resolve significant problems for individuals in the health care system. Contents include identifying health care problems, systemic reviewing up-to-date information, critique and appraisal of concurrent evidence, recognizing and evaluating different options of heath care, and developing an applicable clinical guideline or protocol as the final product. 
 
Master Thesis   6 credits
Students are strongly encouraged to apply scientific research methods in resolving critical problems in current health care system in this course. Students are required to work closely with their advisor to identify important research question, develop a research proposal, conduct the study, collect and analyze data, interpret the results, and write up the final report for submission. 
 
● Elective courses
Special Issues in Maternal-child Nursing  3 credits
The aim of this course is to enhance the role of advanced practice nurses in addressing health issues of children and women based on family-centered care. Students will explore and identify current important issues in obstetric and pediatric nursing through diverse learning activities. Course contents include family assessment, post-delivery care, infant health assessment and care, children’s physical and mental development, nutrition, birth control, women’s health and safe sex practice.
 
Special Issues in Public Health and Health Policy   3 credits
This course explores disease prevention, health maintenance and health promotion associated with special target population using population-based approach. Topics include preventive medicine, environmental health, chronic disease prevention, health policy, community health assessment and intervention, and special issues with vulnerable population and cross-culture care. Topics can be adjusted according to students’ special interests and preferences.
 
Infectious Disease Prevention and Management   3 credits
This course introduces the common health problems, infection and infestations in tropical and subtropical regions, such as Dengue fever, malaria, emerging infectious diseases, tuberculosis and AIDS. The basic pathology, disease prevention, infection control, and medical treatment and management and nursing care will also be discussed.
 
Disaster and Emergency Nursing   3 credits
This course introduces the concepts of disasters and disaster mitigation, and the importance and function of disaster nursing. Emergency care of physical and psychological injury caused by nature or man-made disaster as well as disaster management and prevention at different phases of disaster will be discussed. Major topics include disaster assessment, emergency management, disaster triage, care provision for victims, establishment of emergent service system and informatics sharing system, self-care, and disaster preparedness will be covered in this course.
 
Qualitative Research  3 credits
This course provides an introduction to the theories and methods applied in qualitative research. Students develop the ability to critique literature, explore and integrate research findings in order to apply the knowledge into clinical practice.  Research design along with data gathering and analysis will also be introduced throughout the course. A preliminary research proposal will be generated relevant to the students’ learning interests or individual’s specialty development.
 
Scientific Writing  3 credits
"This course will help the students further refine their scientific reasoning skills in conjunction with basic skills of scientific communication in an English academic environment as they work on their written and oral research proposals. Research material, selected by students and relevant to their individual research projects, will be analyzed by the students to appreciate academic writing conventions."

 








